res where the module lacks response validation.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The classification result for the same document is the same across repeated calls.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The failure mode is inconsistency under real non-determinism. Because the module delegates to an external AI API (which are non-deterministic), the requirement is that repeated calls produce the same result despite the API potentially returning different labels on different runs. To catch a real failure (module doesn't cache or doesn't memoize effectively against a truly non-deterministic API), you must call the real API multiple times. Mocking the API to always return consistent values hides the real failure. Testing against actual API non-determinism requires agentic-level infrastructure.","test_description":"Call the module twice with the same document against the real external API (or a test double that simulates non-determinism). Assert that both calls return the same classification label. Run this test multiple times to account for potential API variation. This catches failures where the module doesn't cache results or doesn't handle real API non-determinism, resulting in inconsistent labels for the same document.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.3,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.65,"Workflow":0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The number of tokens consumed for a typical document stays within the configured per-call budget.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"The failure mode is: a real, typical document causes token usage to exceed the budget. Mocking the API to report arbitrary token counts cannot expose whether actual documents exceed the budget. To catch this failure, you must send a representative document to the real external API and measure the actual token consumption. This requires a real 